            The equation was confirmed by rendering p.4-115 at 9x and reading the grouping BY EYE, not
            off the text layer. Independently reproduced 210/210, worst 0.135%, and the prose 2.5934.
            Same numbers as the earlier session got. Two independent reads agreeing is the evidence.

            🔴 SOURCES.md's CENTRAL CLAIM WAS FALSE, and it was this project's OWN rule that it broke.
            It said the rows verify rests on were "read directly at the publisher's own PDF".
            docs.ips.us is a DISTRIBUTOR's document store: the cover says "Courtesy of store.ips.us",
            the stamp is on all 562 pages, and the metadata shows a 2023 Aspose re render. The SEL row
            is a UNIVERSITY COURSE HANDOUT. So rule #10, "anything the verify phase rests on gets read
            at the publisher's PDF", was written down by the session that earned it and then not
            applied to the primary two lines above it. A RULE THAT LIVES IN PROSE IS A WISH.
            It is a machine checked FIELD now: `Read at` = PUBLISHER / MIRROR / NONE, required by
            check_sources.py. Adding it found the same thing in 3 of 4 projects (9 load bearing rows
            at mirrors). Only 01 reads its primary at the publisher.
            MIRROR IS A WARNING, NOT A FAILURE, on purpose: GE's own download is LOGIN WALLED and GE
            does not offer version 1.6x at all any more, so "read it at the publisher" is not a step
            that was skipped, it is a step that DOES NOT EXIST for this document. A gate that fails
            there only teaches people to lie in the column. Wrong fails; incomplete shows.
            What the confidence actually rests on instead, stated in SOURCES.md: the document agrees
            with itself 211 times (equation -> 210 cells + prose), and GE's F650 manual, a different
            document through a different chain, publishes the identical constants.

            🔴 THE 0.3 TO 0.4 s INTERVAL IS NOT PUBLIC DOMAIN. TM 5-811-14 is a US Army document, so
            the instinct is that all of it is quotable. Para 4-2d carries an ASTERISK: "Reprinted with
            permission from ANSI/IEEE Standard 242-1986 ... copyright 1986 by IEEE." The permission was
            granted to the Army, not to this repo. A DOCUMENT'S LICENCE IS NOT UNIFORM: "it is a
            government document" is a claim about the cover, not about the paragraph. So the number is
            cited and the passage is not reproduced. The method the app DOES report, "ensure no
            overlapping of curves", is para 4-2c(7), OUTSIDE the asterisk, in the Army's own prose.
            Nearly quoted the interleaved text layer's version of that passage, which stitches two
            columns into the sentence "In general only relays, the time interval is usually 0.3-0.4
            seconds". THAT SENTENCE IS NOT IN THE DOCUMENT. Rendered the page and read it instead.

            02 PRINTS NO COORDINATION VERDICT. Same shape as 01 printing no tier. Its own source says
            the interval is "usually" 0.3 to 0.4 s, and an `if` statement turns a rule of thumb into a
            limit the source declined to state, then prints it where it reads as a finding. The band is
            drawn as context; the judgment stays with the reader. verify/ asserts the REFUSAL.

            MUTATION TESTING FOUND THREE THINGS, one of them in the shared tooling.
            (a) tools/mutate.sh trimmed with `xargs`, which PARSES SHELL QUOTING, so any mutant whose
                description held an apostrophe died with "unterminated quote" and printed a BLANK NAME.
                The mutant still ran, so a SURVIVOR could be reported nameless: the one line a person
                needs to act on. Fixed with sed. Affected every project.
            (b) A real coverage hole: swapping the reset equation's literal 2 for the family's p
                SURVIVED, because reset was only tested on Extremely Inverse, whose p IS 2.000. Only
                Moderately Inverse (p=0.02) can see it. A CONSTANT THAT EQUALS A LITERAL CANNOT TEST
                THAT LITERAL.
            (c) A THIRD CATEGORY the runner did not model: an EQUIVALENT MUTANT. `m <= 1` -> `m < 1`
                cannot be killed, because division by zero already returns Infinity at m=1. Not dead
                code, not a coverage hole. PROVED it rather than assuming, deleted the mutant, kept the
                `=` (it states intent), and taught mutate.sh the category. 1 and 2 say "change the
                code"; 3 says "change the mutant", and guessing wrong deletes correct code.

            NO INVENTED TOLERANCE, and six cells explain why the check is written oddly. The criterion
            is the table's own printed precision: half of the last printed digit, 0.0005 s. Six cells
            (all Very Inverse) land on an EXACT rounding tie: VI TDM=0.5 M=1.5 is exactly 8.0895 and GE
            rounds half up to 8.090, while the nearest double is 8.0894999999999992. So "round to 3 and
            demand equality" FAILS on those six for reasons that have nothing to do with protection.
            Also: "calc < 8.0895" is VACUOUS, because the literal 8.0895 IS the same double as calc.
            The check scales by 1000, where the tie 8089.5 is exactly representable and the comparison
            finally means something.

            UI checked structurally, then by eye, and BOTH were needed. The structural pass caught
            curves escaping the viewBox (drawn to 4000 s on a 1000 s axis) -> clipPath. It could not
            see that the band's label sat on top of the downstream curve; the screenshot could. And a
            getBoundingClientRect check on the clipped <g> reported the SAME box clipped or not, i.e.
            the MEASUREMENT could not see clipping at all: a green control that proved nothing.

